  "description": {
    "en": "A perennial plant native to the mountains of East Asia, prized for its fleshy root which has been used in traditional medicine for thousands of years. The root typically resembles a human figure, which is reflected in its Chinese name (人蔘 - 'man root').",
    "zh-Hant": "原產於東亞山區的多年生草本植物，其肉質根部在中醫藥中使用數千年。根形似人形，故名「人蔘」。"
  },
  "habitat": {
    "en": "Cool, shady forests with well-drained, humus-rich soil. Native to Korea, northeastern China, and eastern Russia."
  },
  "origin": {
    "en": "Northeast Asia - Korea, northeastern China (Manchuria), eastern Russia"
  },
  "geographicalDistribution": {
    "en": "Primarily cultivated in Korea, China, and Japan. Wild populations are rare due to overharvesting."
  },
  "growthForm": "herb",
  "lifecycle": "perennial",
